cales in\nthe nearby flocculent spiral galaxy NGC300, contrary to their tight correlation\non galactic scales. We demonstrate that this de-correlation implies rapid\nevolutionary cycling between GMCs, star formation, and feedback. We apply a\nnovel statistical method to quantify the evolutionary timeline and find that\nstar formation is regulated by efficient stellar feedback, driving GMC\ndispersal on short timescales (~1.5 Myr) due to radiation and stellar winds,\nprior to supernova explosions. This feedback limits GMC lifetimes to about one\ndynamical timescale (~10 Myr), with integrated star formation efficiencies of\nonly 2-3%. Our findings reveal that galaxies consist of building blocks\nundergoing vigorous, feedback-driven lifecycles, that vary with the galactic\nenvironment and collectively define how galaxies form stars. Systematic\napplications of this multi-scale analysis to large galaxy samples will provide\nkey input for a predictive, bottom-up theory of galaxy formation and evolution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 21 May 2019 18:00:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 23 May 2019 08:48:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-24"}
